 on different issues that you=E2=80=99re following right now. You could do =
that with a generative model at some point, maybe even today, but you could=
 also just generate pure text and information based on what=E2=80=99s out t=
here on the Internet if you=E2=80=99re really interested in a very niche to=
pic. I find that future so enthralling.

*Right, because it=E2=80=99s like cutting out the middleman, right? Instead=
 of trying to collect a bunch of almost right articles that are in your int=
erest, wouldn=E2=80=99t it be great to pull everything out of them and just=
 give you the one-page summary of what happened in F1 yesterday or whatever=
 it might be? But this is the question for all this sort of stuff, what abo=
ut the source publications? Right now the worst part of Artifact is all the=
 ads in the articles. You can go to reader mode, but it=E2=80=99s under a m=
enu probably because you don=E2=80=99t want to make publishers mad. What te=
nsion do you feel versus the long term source of your knowledge, versus how=
 you reveal it?*

*KS:* I=E2=80=99m watching all of these lawsuits closely. There=E2=80=99s t=
he guy who publishes code and says, =E2=80=9CHey, wait. GitHub CoPilot, bas=
ically somewhere in there is my code, I swear.=E2=80=9D And then you have a=
rtists looking at Dall-E thinking =E2=80=9CSomewhere in there is my art=E2=
=80=9D. I think that=E2=80=99s a real issue we=E2=80=99re going to have to =
grapple with. Not we, Artifact, we, society. And I don=E2=80=99t have all t=
he answers, but it=E2=80=99s going to be interesting to watch it play out. =
In no shape or form do we wake up in the morning saying, =E2=80=9COur goal =
is to replace publishers=E2=80=9D, because it turns out reported content fr=
om the front lines with interesting, thoughtful, unique analysis that you c=
an=E2=80=99t get anywhere else is not something you can simply parrot out w=
ith a model and so I think that a lot of people are going to have job secur=
ity for a very long time in the publishing industry because of that.

At the same time, I think there=E2=80=99s this really interesting opportuni=
ty to allow for people to publish more easily, more quickly on topics, that=
 may not be economical today. It=E2=80=99s the simple Amazon thing. For the=
 longest time, you could only buy bestsellers and all these mom-and-pop boo=
kstores but all of a sudden it was economical to sell interesting =E2=80=94=
 whether it=E2=80=99s fan fiction or a specific genre =E2=80=94 I actually =
think we=E2=80=99ll see more production in the long run, human production, =
because we can find audiences with this system than we would=E2=80=99ve wit=
hout this system. And I think that=E2=80=99s a bright future for publishing=
, not a scary one. But Mike, we=E2=80=99ve talked a lot about this, what do=
 you think?

*MK:* I think I keep coming back and this is probably something I think may=
 resonate with your own experience, Ben: I think a lot of the value of grea=
t reporting or great content online comes from the personality or the persp=
ective. It=E2=80=99s the writers that I keep coming back to over and over a=
nd over again on a topic and sure, maybe GPT-4 is going to be able to mimic=
 the ideas well enough that it=E2=80=99s hard to tease them apart. But in g=
eneral, there are either sources of analysis or voices or perspectives that=
 I think differentiate, and I think that is if not irreplaceable, just very=
 hard to replace and just that has that human aspect to it. The more we can=
 find those voices =E2=80=94 and those voices could be writing for a major =
publication, they could have their own blog, they could be starting their o=
wn blog now =E2=80=94 and I think that is the human element that I get most=
 excited about. If we could make their lives easier, that would be awesome,=
 if we can find them an audience, that would be great. I=E2=80=99ve already=
 seen that happen even in our beta test in early days. I actually had no id=
ea this publication existed and I really like it, it=E2=80=99s covering the=
 war in Ukraine really closely in a way that I hadn=E2=80=99t heard of befo=
re. Sports analysis =E2=80=94 I=E2=80=99ve discovered sports writers that I=
 hadn=E2=80=99t been exposed to before and I keep coming back to.

So I put my vote or my belief firmly in the writers=E2=80=99 corner, regard=
less of exactly what medium they=E2=80=99re being positioned in. And yes, I=
 think there=E2=80=99s a long tail on local, this has been tread before, an=
d a long tail on interests where either factual reporting or summarization =
on things that aren=E2=80=99t economical to do from a human perspective, wi=
ll be useful. I was reading, I think it=E2=80=99s Neal Stephenson=E2=80=99s=
, not his latest novel, it=E2=80=99s two novels ago, and there=E2=80=99s th=
is concept of social media editors and the wealthy people get humans to edi=
t their social media feeds for them. If you=E2=80=99re not as well off, you=
 have to rely on a public algorithm, and it=E2=80=99s dystopian in that way=
.

But there=E2=80=99s just way too much content out there for any single pers=
on to consume or even summarize and that=E2=80=99s where I think that if I =
can be a little bit more succinct, connect people to interesting writers an=
d have them fall in love with them and have them form the long-term relatio=
nship and especially in places where it=E2=80=99s economical for that write=
r to make a living and hopefully can make that easier over time. Then, ther=
e=E2=80=99s a lot of other things like just giving summarization or generat=
ional leg up, will just help people stay more informed on their long tail.

*Yeah, obviously I=E2=80=99m biased because I think that will hopefully be =
the outcome as well. I will say there=E2=80=99s a whole middle layer here t=
hat is super annoying. The whole headlines that are questions and don=E2=80=
=99t tell you the answer and I get mad in Artifact because of course I want=
 to click it but I don=E2=80=99t want to reward them in the algorithm and t=
hink that they got any sort of attention. So I=E2=80=99m like training a pe=
t here or something along those lines, but that=E2=80=99s what happens, the=
 Internet. The middle gets wiped out and this certainly seems a push to ori=
ginal content and finding that and surfacing it and perhaps rewriting it, b=
ut these intervening layers that give you the opportunity to have a cold st=
art might not be very viable in the long run. I could end it there unless y=
ou have any final words, I appreciate you taking the time.*

*KS:* I do have a thought on that because I was speaking with a guy who did=
 the algorithm at Instagram. His nickname actually internally was literally=
 =E2=80=9CThe Algorithm=E2=80=9D and we talked a lot about recommender syst=
ems early on. One of the points he had is that the way these algorithms are=
 trained, the objective function that you give these algorithms to optimize=
, ends up having this strange, almost tertiary effect that it forces conten=
t creators to start creating content that fits what the algorithm wants to =
optimize for.

It=E2=80=99s why in TikTok, at the end, have you ever seen these videos? I=
=E2=80=99m sure you have, where literally at the end they say, =E2=80=9CAnd=
 that=E2=80=99s why=E2=80=9D, and then the beginning words of the video are=
 like, =E2=80=9CYou always cook chicken in butter=E2=80=9D, or whatever and=
 it loops and it feels perfectly loopable and they do that because they nee=
d more repeat view so that the algorithm goes, =E2=80=9COh, I have a winner=
 here and I=E2=80=99m going to show it to more people.=E2=80=9D So the way =
you train your algorithm ends up forcing people to create a certain type of=
 content, and what we have to be very careful with, I think on this particu=
lar point, is to not reward behavior where you obfuscate the actual content=
 of the article, aka clickbait, where people write more sensationalist head=
lines or more sensationalist articles.

If we get big enough, there=E2=80=99s a real consideration on how we train =
the algorithm and what objective function we get or give it, and what conte=
nt gets produced for it. We need to be very mindful of that because what I=
=E2=80=99d rather have is a world where we have more original content, more=
 interesting content, and less of this gaming-the-algorithm content and it=
=E2=80=99s a trap that every social network falls into. But again, we start=
ed this talk by talking about what it=E2=80=99s like to be a second-time fo=
under. We=E2=80=99ve seen a few things and what=E2=80=99s nice about going =
through this a second time is we have that in mind when we=E2=80=99re build=
ing it so hopefully we can avoid some of those pitfalls.

*Sounds good. Well, Kevin and Mike, I appreciate you coming on and taking t=
he time. Thanks for coming on.*

*KS:* Thank you very much.

